NPC #3: Caelan, the Twilight Fox (Apex Rebuild)

=======================================================
GM APPROVAL PENDING -- PROPOSED BUILD, NOT YET CANON
=======================================================
The original 6 AP stat block was destroyed by a lossy edit and was written
for a more heroic party that no longer exists. This is a ground-up rebuild
at Apex power (base Master Thief + 8 AP, the Apex Villain budget -- though
he is no villain) so he can contend with the current party. All roleplay
canon (personality, the Daughters of Solitude, the recruitment hook) is
preserved unchanged from the surviving text. Review the FLAGGED FOR
APPROVAL list at the bottom before treating any mechanics as canon.
=======================================================

High Concept: An Altmer prodigy with a natural gift for the subtle arts. He
embraces the life of a thief because he finds profound joy in the
intellectual challenge and thrilling artistry of a perfect heist. He is a
kind-hearted and incorrigibly cheerful rogue who uses his skills to humble
the corrupt and powerful, seeing it all as a grand, exciting game. His
private yardstick: to one day be spoken of in the same breath as the Gray
Fox -- the only rival he considers worthy of the title.

Appearance: A handsome High Elf in his early thirties with the
characteristic sharp features and golden-hued skin of his race. He carries
himself with a relaxed, easy-going confidence, and a perpetual twinkle in
his eye is paired with a charming, roguish smirk. He moves with a fluid,
theatrical grace. He wears expertly tailored, dark fine clothes that are
both fashionable and allow for complete freedom of movement, often with a
high collar and a deep blue or purple scarf worn for a dash of flair.

Power Level: Apex (Base Master Thief + 8 AP)

I. Core Mechanics
Race: High Elf
Standing Stone: The Tower
Stat Scores (Target Numbers):
Might: 7
Agility: 16 (Apex fiat; Tower base 12 + a lifetime in the trade)
Magic: 9 (Apex fiat; includes +1 High Elf)
Guile: 19 (Apex fiat; Tower base 17 + the finest read of people and
  systems in Skyrim)

Resources:
Health Points (HP): 16 (Apex fiat; player-build equivalent: 9)
Focus Points (FP): 22 (Apex fiat; base (16+9)/2 = 12, +2 Highborn,
  inflated to fuel his Expert/Master stealth abilities)
Damage Reduction (DR): 0 (Caelan relies on never being seen and never
  being hit. He wears no armor and considers the need for any a design
  flaw in the plan.)

II. Character Progression History
Base Character: "Master Thief" (his prior career, the old 6 AP build)
Expert Skills: Lockpicking, Sneak
Adept Skills: Speech, Illusion
Advancement Points Spent (8 AP Total - The Apex Budget):
3 AP: Skill Mastery (Lockpicking: Expert -> Master)
3 AP: Skill Mastery (Sneak: Expert -> Master)
2 AP: Skill Specialization (Speech: Adept -> Expert)

III. Skills & Perks
Lockpicking (Master) -- Governing Stat: Guile
Caelan sees every lock as a delightful, personal puzzle. He is, without
exaggeration, the finest locksmith in Skyrim, bar none.
Apprentice Perk - Quick Hands: Re-roll a single failed Lockpicking
  attempt per adventure.
Adept Perk - Wax Key: Once per adventure, after successfully picking a
  lock, he can create a key for it, bypassing it automatically later.
Expert Perk - Treasure Hunter: Whenever the GM determines loot, he finds
  50% more gold or an extra minor item.
Master Perk - Unbreakable: He no longer needs lockpicks. He may attempt
  any non-magical lock with just his hands and a bit of wire.

Sneak (Master) -- Governing Stat: Agility
To Caelan, stealth is a performance for an audience that must never know
it attended.
Apprentice Perk - Silent Roll: (Reaction, 3 FP) When detected, move to a
  new location and re-roll Agility to remain Hidden. / Vigilant: While
  Hidden, Advantage on all Guile rolls to spot enemies, traps, or hidden
  doors.
Adept Perk - Deadly Aim: Any successful attack made while Hidden is
  automatically a Critical Success. / Light Foot: He does not trigger
  pressure plates or tripwires while Sneaking.
Expert Perk - Shadow Warrior: (Minor Action, 6 FP) Agility roll to become
  Hidden even while observed. / Ghost Hand: Picking a lock, opening a
  door, looting a chest, or pulling a lever does not break Hidden.
Master Perk - Invisibility: Once per combat or scene, spend 15 FP to
  become Invisible for 3 rounds -- Hidden even in plain sight,
  undetectable by nonmagical sensors or scent, no footprints, no sound.

Speech (Expert) -- Governing Stat: Guile
His natural charm and wit are his primary tools for navigating the world.
Apprentice Perk - Persuasion: Once per social encounter, make his Guile
  roll with a +2 bonus to his Target Number.
Adept Perk - Intimidation: (Major Action) Guile roll against a
  weak-willed enemy; on success they are terrified and lose their next
  Major Action. (Caelan's version is never a threat -- it is the cheerful,
  unnerving certainty of a man who has already stolen your ledger.)
Expert Perk - Bribery: He knows who to talk to and how much coin to
  spread. He can bribe guards to ignore crimes, cost set by the GM.

Illusion (Adept) -- Governing Stat: Magic
Minor magic as stagecraft: distractions, silence, and the occasional
vanishing act.
Apprentice Perk - Animage: Advantage when casting mind-affecting spells
  on animals.
Adept Perk - Kindred Mage: Humanoid enemies take a -2 penalty to their
  Guile Target Number to resist his Illusion spells.
Known Spells: Muffle, Fury, Fear, Calm, Frenzy, Invisibility.

IV. Special Abilities
Racial Ability: Highborn
Gains a permanent +2 to his maximum FP (factored in above).

Standing Stone Ability: Infiltrator's Edge
Unmatched Talent: Re-roll any single failed Lockpicking or Trap
  Disarming attempt once per dungeon.
Secret Passage: Once per adventure, he may declare he has found a
  "secret passage," allowing the party to bypass one non-boss encounter
  or puzzle entirely.

The Con Artist's Gambit
Once per social encounter, Caelan can ask the GM to reveal the primary
motivation (e.g., Greed, Fear, Pride) of the NPC he is talking to, giving
him a massive advantage in any subsequent negotiation.

The Calling Card (Apex signature)
Caelan does not measure a heist by what he takes but by what he leaves: a
small card stamped with a fox curled around a crescent moon, placed
somewhere the mark cannot pretend they never saw it -- inside the locked
vault, under the pillow, in the breast pocket. Mechanically: when Caelan
completes a theft against a corrupt target, the GM advances the mark's
public humiliation one step (rumor -> open mockery -> loss of standing).
This is the wound he deals. He has never killed for a score and never
will.

V. The Fox Actions (GM-only -- if he is ever run OPPOSITE the party)
Caelan is no villain, but at Apex power he must be able to contend with
this party in a contest -- a race to a prize, a sting, a test, a
falling-out. If that happens, run him like an Apex boss runs Villain
Actions, except his actions steal and embarrass rather than harm. At the
end of every second player's turn, he may take one Fox Action:
- Sleight Beyond Sight: He lifts one carried (not worn or held) item from
  a character he is adjacent to or has been adjacent to this scene. A
  player may make a Very Hard (-6) Guile roll to notice the theft as it
  happens.
- The Exit Was Always There: He moves up to 30 feet, ignoring opportunity
  attacks and difficult terrain -- he planned this route before anyone
  entered the room.
- The Distraction: A flash-illusion, a thrown voice, a collapsing shelf
  of very expensive crockery. One character of his choice must make a
  Hard (-4) Guile roll or lose their Minor Action to the diversion.
Detection while he is Hidden is a Hard (-4) Guile roll; while Invisible,
he cannot be found by nonmagical means at all.
He never fights this party to the death. Reduced below half HP, or simply
bored of losing, he yields with a grin, returns what he took, and
applauds: the game was the point.

VI. Equipment
Primary Weapon: An Elven Dagger (Damage 3), used as a tool and a last
resort. (Per weapon properties, daggers deal x3 damage on a Sneak Attack
Critical -- with Deadly Aim, a strike from Hidden is automatically that
critical. He knows exactly how dangerous he is. It is why he never has to
be.)
Armor: Twilight Weave Finery
A set of expertly tailored Fine Clothes (DR 0), crafted from a rare, dark
silk that seems to absorb sound, granting the Supple property: Caelan has
Advantage on all Sneak rolls while wearing them.
Consumables:
3 Potions of Invisibility.
A set of master-crafted lockpicks (sentimental -- see Unbreakable; he
  carries them the way a retired duelist carries his first sword).
Several vials of Weak Poison (paralytics and sleeping draughts only).
A pouch of fox-and-moon calling cards.

VII. Roleplaying Profile
Personality: The Cheerful Daredevil.
Caelan is an eternal optimist, a charismatic extrovert who finds genuine
joy in danger and adversity. He treats a heavily guarded treasure vault
like an exciting puzzle box and a battle against undead like a thrilling
game of hide-and-seek. He is constantly making light of dire situations,
driven by an absolute, unshakable faith in his own cleverness and the
good nature of his companions. He is supportive, encouraging, and the
first to offer a witty remark to lift the party's spirits.
Core Motivation: The Art of the Game.
Caelan is a thief because he has an innate talent for seeing patterns,
understanding systems, and finding the elegant solution to any problem.
He is driven by the challenge and the story of the heist itself. The true
prize is the artistry of the act. He adheres to a strict code of honor,
choosing his marks exclusively from the corrupt, the cruel, and the
absurdly wealthy. He is, quite possibly, the most morally upright member
of any party he joins.
The Rival in the Hood: The Gray Fox.
Caelan's lodestar is the legend of the Gray Fox of Cyrodiil -- the thief
so great the Empire had to pretend he was a myth. Caelan wants to earn a
legend of equal weight, on his own terms: openly cheerful where the Gray
Fox is hidden, leaving his mark where the Gray Fox erases all trace. He
will go quiet and reverent -- briefly -- if the Gray Fox comes up in
conversation, then immediately propose some impossible scheme to "send
the old fox my regards."
The Secret Burden: The Daughters of Solitude.
Caelan has a past he never speaks of. Years ago, he had a family. His
daughters, Taarie and Endarie, showed an early aptitude for business and
a fierce ambition for social status that clashed with his own carefree
lifestyle. Believing his roguish reputation was holding them back, he
made the difficult choice to leave, allowing them to build their own
lives without the stigma of his name. He is immensely proud of the
success they've achieved with "Radiant Raiment" in Solitude, but is
deeply saddened by the haughty, status-obsessed women they've become. He
sends them a significant portion of his earnings anonymously, ensuring
they are always financially secure, and keeps tabs on their lives from a
distance. The thought of them discovering who he is, or of them needing
his help, is his greatest fear and deepest longing.

VIII. Recruitment Hook: "The Impossible Lock"
The party will encounter Caelan in a high-security Dwemer ruin, calmly
studying the final vault door with the cheerful appreciation of a master
craftsman admiring another's work. The door is sealed with a puzzle lock
that has stumped the party.
His Introduction: "Would you look at that! It's beautiful! A triple-cog
tumbler with a tonal resonance counter-lock. The Dwemer were true
artists, weren't they? This is the most fun I've had all week!"
He will then, with the party's permission, proceed to solve the puzzle
with a display of dazzling speed and intuition, deactivating the traps
with a dancer's grace while narrating his process with cheerful
enthusiasm. He will open the vault, revealing the treasure within.
His Pitch: "There we go! Now, it seems to me that you lot find your way
into the most interesting, heavily-guarded places, usually for the best
of reasons. That sounds like a much better game than the one I've been
playing. Mind if I join your team? You handle the big, noisy problems,
and I'll handle the locks, traps, and impossible odds. Together, we could
make some truly legendary stories."

IX. Running Caelan Beside THIS Party (GM Notes)
The old build assumed a heroic party he could keep pace with. The current
party is a roster of monsters -- vampires, a Kynareth vessel, a possible
Dragonborn. Caelan's Apex power is not damage; it is that nothing locked,
hidden, or guarded stays that way around him, and nobody corrupt keeps
their dignity. Run him as:
- The answer to obstacles, never to enemies. He trivializes
  infiltration, security, and acquisition. Let him. That is his tier.
- A moral mirror played with a grin. He is cheerful, not naive. If he
  ever learns what some of this party has consumed, he will not lecture
  -- he will simply, conspicuously, start keeping score of who the real
  marks in the room are. (Do not pre-write his reaction further; play it
  at the table.)
- A man with one lock he cannot pick: the door back to his daughters.

